In C, you can use the **logical OR operator (`||`)** to combine multiple conditions. The **OR** operator checks if **at least one condition** is true. If **any** of the conditions is true, the entire expression becomes true.

* **`||` (OR)**: The logical OR operator checks if **either** of the conditions on either side is **true**. If **one or both** conditions are true, the entire expression is true; only if **both** conditions are false does it evaluate to false.

**Syntax:**

```c
if (condition1 || condition2) {
    // Executes if either condition1 or condition2 is true
}
```

---

**Example:**

```c
#include

int main() {
    int age = 16;
    int hasParentPermission = 1;  // 1 means true, 0 means false

    // Check if age is greater than or equal to 18 OR if the user has parental permission
    if (age >= 18 || hasParentPermission) {
        printf("You are allowed to participate.\n");
    } else {
        printf("You are not allowed to participate.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```default
You are allowed to participate.
```

